english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent to Gyeol Ri-mun Upon His Departure
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Law exists to carry out governance, and the harmonious use of human compassion and law together represents the highest form of statecraft. When the Sacred Dynasty arose, it had not yet established a unified legal code. Only after the New Ordinances emerged in Zhiyuan and the Comprehensive Statutes were compiled in Zhizhi did officials have something to uphold and the common people know what to avoid.

    Gyeol, of Xujiang, bears the name of Loyalty and is renowned throughout the world as a learned Confucian. There is no branch of knowledge—whether in writing or the practical arts—that he has not mastered, and he especially excels in the study of law and names. The former Prime Minister of the Eastern Province recognized his talents early and memorialized the court on his behalf. In the third year of Zhiyuan, he was appointed Examiner of the Province, and I too was summoned to serve as an officer at the same time, receiving appointment on the same day.

    Gyeol then spoke to me, saying: "When governance flows from many sources, the people cannot bear the burden of command. Now that all four seas are one household, why does the law of the Middle Kingdom not prevail in this Eastern land?" I replied: "Goryeo is the ancient land of the Three Hans, whose customs and speech differ from those of the Central Lands. Its dress, ceremonies, and rites form their own distinct system, one that has remained unchanged since the Qin and Han dynasties. Now, under the Sacred Dynasty, we are bound in the relation of uncle and nephew, favored as father and son. The governance of people and the administration of justice are allowed to follow the old ways, while we do not interfere in their administrative affairs. All the authority of a nation and the power of a province rest entirely with the King and his Chancellor—consider the trust and honor bestowed upon them!

    Recently, however, the national law has grown slack and the people's virtue ever more shallow. They sow chaos among themselves and compete in accusation and denunciation. Those provincial officials who uphold the Comprehensive Statutes declare: 'Under heaven, all lands belong to the king.' Those national ministers who preserve the old laws counter: 'The World Emperor left instruction that the customs of each land should not be altered.' Thus they shift from that to this, abandon what is weighty for what is light, each with their own justifications, until no one knows which path to follow. Does not the failure of law arise from this very confusion?"

    Gyeol replied: "Indeed. Having received my mandate, I know only to uphold the law." And so it came to pass that his administration became exemplary in clarity, petitions ceased to be answered through favoritism, officials abandoned their private interests, and the people submitted willingly to his impartial justice. Without losing sight of the great principles of the court, he never disturbed the ancient customs of our land. Thus I witnessed in him the true harmony of compassion and law.

    This year, as winter brings the end of his term, and as he yearns for his aging parents, thoughts of return have stirred his heart. All who know him say there should be verses composed in his honor. They have asked me for a preface, and so I commit to writing these words above, to present them as he departs. I must also mention his elder brother, the Minister of the Collected Words, who has become the foremost scholar of our age, his name known throughout the realm. I had the honor of studying under his guidance, and when I journeyed eastward, I received his teachings, which I have carried in my heart both day and night without forgetting. Only now do I understand that I have not betrayed his trust. When you return, I beg you to convey my gratitude to him.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Sacred Dynasty' refers to the Yuan Dynasty under Mongol rule, which exercised sovereignty over Goryeo during this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Eastern Province' (征東省) was the administrative division of Yuan-ruled Goryeo, with the position of Examiner (理問) being a judicial or administrative office.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Hans' refers to the ancient Korean kingdoms of Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla, emphasizing Goryeo's distinct cultural heritage.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'uncle and nephew' (舅甥) reflects the complex tributary relationship between Goryeo and Yuan, where political ties were sometimes expressed through kinship metaphors.
